 zone_managed_pages(zone)
 
 zone_managed_pages(zone)

It’s a macro (a little helper) defined by the Linux kernel.

Purpose: tell you how many memory pages a zone manages.

A “page” is the basic unit of memory (usually 4 KB).

So if zone_managed_pages(zone) returns 1000, it means that zone has 1000 × 4 KB = 4 MB of memory.




if (!populated_zone(zone))
    continue;
populated_zone(zone)

This is a macro (helper) from the kernel.

It checks if the zone actually has memory pages.

Returns true if the zone exists and has memory, false if it’s empty.

!populated_zone(zone)

The ! means NOT.

So this is true when the zone is empty.


if (!populated_zone(zone))
    continue;

Plain English:

“If this zone has no memory, skip it and check the next zone.”


✅ Big Picture Summary

The module loops over memory nodes (buildings).

For each node, it loops over memory zones (floors).

Skips empty zones.

Prints zone name and how many memory pages it has.

Cleans up on unload

